  "overall_read": "This reads as a personal affirmation or self-coaching mantra rooted in mindfulness, self-compassion, and boundary-setting. It has a gentle, grounding cadence and aims to counter people-pleasing tendencies by prioritizing internal awareness over external demands. It lands as sincere and centering, though somewhat abstract—it might feel empowering or vague depending on the reader's familiarity with contemplative practice.",
  "where_it_helps": "It helps individuals prone to neglecting their own needs in favor of others, especially in high-stress or codependent dynamics. It can serve as a quick reset during moments of anxiety, social pressure, or emotional overwhelm. It reinforces the habit of pausing before reacting, which can reduce impulsive decisions and foster emotional regulation.",
  "where_it_could_mislead": "If taken rigidly, it could justify withdrawing from necessary social responsibilities or interpreting any discomfort as a sign to disengage. It might be misused to avoid constructive conflict or to rationalize self-absorption under the guise of self-care. The phrase 'staying connected to myself first' could also be misinterpreted as permission to disregard empathy or accountability toward others in important relationships."
